surveys.narrative: The 1994 Teepee Lake population assessment occurred as a result of angler complaints concerning poor troutfishing. Teepee Lake is located in the Chippewa National Forest off the Woodtick Trail and is one of fivedesignated stream trout lakes managed in the Walker area. The Lake is 18 acres in size and has a maximum depthof 18 feet. Rainbow trout (RBT) is the only species of trout found in Teepee Lake and are the result of stocking.A total of nine RBT were sampled in 1994 that ranged in length from 8.3 - 11.9 inches. In 1993 only two RBT weresampled. In 1992 16 RBT were sampled.No other species of fish was sampled in the nets.

Teepee Lake (11-0312-00 Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 18.05 acres and a shoreline length of 0.92 miles. There is a US Forest Service public access on the northeast shore of the lake. Teepee Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area that is stocked annually with rainbow trout. The trout population in Teepee Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake. Prior to 2006, DNR staff had stocked fingerling trout in the fall, but beginning in 2006, a switch was made to spring stocking of yearlings in an effort to improve over-winter survival.

Six rainbow trout were captured in the 2006 DNR survey. The mean length of these fish was 12 inches and their lengths ranged from 11 to 13 inches.

Since 1998, Fisheries personnel have been sampling zooplankton, the tiny animals on which Teepee Lake rainbow trout feed. The quantity of zooplankton available in Teepee Lake is relatively low and biologists are currently investigating the annual fluctuation in trout survival by examining the food supply.

Teepee Lake is one of four designated stream trout lakes in the Walker area. It is located three miles south and one mile west of Whipholt. Other stream trout lakes are Perch (located in the Foothills State Forest), Hazel (located four miles west of Longville), and Willard (located three miles north and two miles east of Backus) Lakes. Teepee Lake has been a designated trout lake since 1957. All trout existing in Teepee Lake are the result of stocking. With the exception of 1965 when brook trout were stocked, rainbow trout have been only species stocked into Teepee Lake. The 1995 Teepee Lake assessment occurred as a result of angler complaints of poor fishing. A total of 14 rainbow trout were sampled in 1995. These trout ranged in length from 6.85 to 15.7 inches and had an average length and weight of 9.1 inches and 0.34 pounds. In 1994, nine rainbow trout were captured, and in 1993 only two trout were sampled.

Teepee Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. It has had this designation since 1957. Other trout lakes in the Walker area are Hazel (located 3.5 miles west of Longville), Willard (located two miles east and two miles north of Backus), Perch (located 5 miles west of Backus), and Diamond (located five miles north and three miles east of Hackensack). All trout existing in the Teepee Lake are the result of stocking. Various strains of rainbow trout have been stocked over the years. For the past several years, anglers have reported poor angling success in Teepee Lake.Testnetting results in 1999 sampled eleven rainbow trout. Trout ranged in length from 8.0 to 15.5 inches. Ten of the trout sampled were one year old while the other trout was two years old. In 1998 and 1999, at various times through the summer, the lake was sampled for zooplankton (tiny animals that are important food for trout). In 1998, low numbers of zooplankton were found. In 1999, the lake continued to have low numbers of zooplankton.

Teepee Lake is an 18-acre lake with 0.92 miles of shoreline and a maximum depth of 31 feet located northeast of Hackensack, MN. There is a US Forest Service public access located on the north shore. Teepee Lake offers Rainbow Trout fishing in a remote, wilderness setting. The lake is entirely within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Teepee Lake is one of four designated stream trout lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area. Other stream trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Diamond, Hazel, and Perch Lakes.

Rainbow Trout were initially stocked in Teepee Lake in 1984. Rainbow Trout do not reproduce in the lake and the population is supported entirely by stocking to provide a unique angling opportunity. Rainbow Trout stocking success is dependent on the absence of introduced species. The average length of Rainbow Trout sampled in 2023 was 12 inches, and lengths ranged from 10 to 16 inches.

People can have significant impacts on lakes and the fish populations they support. Harvest, lakeshore development, removal of shoreline vegetation, and introductions of invasive species can all adversely affect fish populations. Currently no aquatic invasive species (AIS) have been identified in Teepee Lake. AIS are moved from infested to non-infested waters by anglers, boaters, and lake shore owners and can adversely impact lakes and fish populations. To avoid spreading AIS, lake users are required to remove all aquatic plants or animals from their watercraft and drain all water from their boat before leaving the access. If you suspect an infestation of an invasive species in this lake, save a specimen and report it to a local natural resource office. Additional information on all of these topics can be found on the DNR website (www.dnr.state.mn.us) or by contacting the Walker Area Fisheries office.

Status of the Fishery Tepee Lk (11-312)This population assessment was done because of reports from anglers that rainbow trout were not being caught inTepee during May, 1993. During the DNR's assessment netting in June, 1993, only two trout, both around 9 incheslong, were caught in four gill net sets. This catch was much lower than catches in 1986, 1989, and 1992. All rainbow trout in Tepee are fish that have been stocked. During most years Tepee Lake provides excellentfishing for stocked rainbow trout. However, because of the low catches during this assessment, the number oftrout stocked in fall 1993 was increased by one-third.

Teepee Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. Other lakes in the Walker area are Diamond, Hazel, Perch, and Willard. Teepee Lake was first managed as a stream-trout lake in 1957. A fair amount of angling pressure has occurred on Teepee Lake, however anglers have reported poor fishing success. About the same number of rainbow trout fingerlings have been stocked in Teepee Lake every year since 1986. During 2000 testnetting, two year classes of rainbow trout were sampled with the majority of fish from the 1999 stocking. The average length of rainbow trout sampled was 9.56 inches though fish ranged from 8 to 15 inches. The lack of older fish could be related to the low numbers and biomass of zooplankton which is an important food source for rainbow trout.

Teepee Lake (11-312; Lake Class 21) also known as Cranberry Lake has a total surface area of 18.1 acres and a shoreline length of 0.8 miles. There is a US Forest Service owned public access on the northeast shore of the lake. Teepee Lake is one of five lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area designated as a stream trout lake and stocked annually. Three rainbow trout were collected in the 2002 population assessment, these fish ranged in size from 8.8 to 16.1 inches. The catch rate for 2002 was 0.75 fish/ net, which is considerably lower than the management goal of 10-20 rainbow trout/ net. Fishing success has been low in recent years on Teepee Lake. Biologists at the Walker Fisheries office are currently investigating the poor trout survival by examining the food supply.

Teepee Lake is one of four designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area. It has had this distinction since 1957. All trout existing in the lake are the result of stocking. With the exception of a 1965 stocking of brook trout, rainbow trout was the only species of trout stocked in Teepee Lake. For the past two years anglers have been compaining about poor fishing. There is a concern that rainbow trout are not surviving long enough to be harvested by anglers. Fall electrofishing and gillnetting were employed to try to obtain a sample of rainbow trout. No were sampled in either effort. Two experimental gillnets didn't sample any kind of fish. Fall electrofishing sampled thousands of minnows but no trout. The minnows were mostly fatheads.

Teepee Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker area, and has been managed for trout since 1957. Other trout lakes in the Walker fisheries area are Diamond (located 5 miles north and 3 miles east of Hackensack), Hazel (located 3.5 miles west of Longville), Perch (located 5 miles west of Backus) and Willard (located 2 miles east and 2 miles north of Backus). All trout in Teepee Lake are the result of stocking. This lake has been stocked with rainbow trout each year since it was reclaimed in 1984. For several years anglers have reported poor fishing success in Teepee Lake.Twenty trout, ranging from 6 to 15 inches, were sampled by DNR test nets in 1998. Catch rates of trout in test nets have varied considerably from 1986 through 1998, however the 1998 rate (10 trout per test net) was near the average of the past eight surveys. At various times throughout the summer, Teepee Lake was sampled for zooplankton (tiny animals that are important food for trout). Low numbers of zooplankton were found. Monitoring of the zooplankton and the trout populations will be done again in 1999.

Teepee Lake (DOW# 11-0312; Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 20.9 acres and a shoreline length of 0.92 miles. There is a Chippewa National Forest Service (CNF) owned public access on the northeast shore of the lake on a CNF Trail. Teepee Lake offers Rainbow Trout fishing in a remote, wilderness-like setting. The lake is totally within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Because of its small size, the lake is ideal for canoes or float tubes. Teepee Lake is one of four lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area stocked annually with Rainbow Trout. The other designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Diamond, Hazel, and Perch Lakes.

Teepee Lake was first used as a stream-trout lake in 1957. It was reclaimed in 1984 and stocked annually with Rainbow Trout. Rainbow Trout do not reproduce in this lake and the population is instead supported entirely by stocking to provide unique angling opportunities. The single Rainbow Trout sampled in 2014 was 12.5 inches and was likely from the spring 2013 stocking. Catch rates were down for the second year indicating poor survival occurred. In 2015 anglers should expect few large fish but catch opportunities will be present following the 2015 spring stocking. In January 2015 Teepee Lake was opened to winter Trout fishing, providing increased opportunities for trout anglers in the Walker area.

Teepee Lake (11-312; Lake Class 21) has a total surface area of 18.05 acres, a shoreline length of 0.92 miles, and a maximum depth of 31 feet. There is a US Forest Service public access on the northeast shore of the lake. Teepee Lake offers good rainbow trout fishing in a remote, wilderness-like setting. The lake is totally within the Chippewa National Forest and the shoreline is undeveloped. Because of its small size, the lake is ideal for canoes or float tubes. Teepee Lake is one of five designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Fisheries Management Area that are stocked annually with rainbow trout. The other designated stream-trout lakes in the Walker Management Area are Diamond, Perch, Teepee and Willard Lakes. The trout population in Teepee Lake depends upon stocking because rainbow trout do not naturally reproduce in this lake.

In 2008, twenty-four rainbow trout were captured, which met the long-range management goal for Teepee Lake. The mean length was 12 inches and the lengths ranged from 10 to 15 inches. Historically, rainbows greater than 15 inches in length have been sampled in several assessments.

Since 1998, Fisheries personnel have been sampling zooplankton, a significant food source for rainbow trout. The quantity of zooplankton available in Teepee Lake is relatively low and biologists are currently investigating the relationship of stocking rates and the size of trout stocked to the abundance of large zooplankton and trout survival in stream-trout lakes.
